{{Orphan|date=July 2016}}
In [[graph theory]], a '''bound graph''' expresses which pairs of elements of some [[partially ordered set]] have an [[upper bound]]. Rigorously, any [[Graph (discrete mathematics)|graph]] ''G'' is a bound graph if there exists a partial order ≤ on the [[vertex (graph theory)|vertices]] of ''G'' with the property that for any vertices ''u'' and ''v'' of ''G'', ''uv'' is an [[edge (graph theory)|edge]] of ''G'' if and only if ''u'' ≠ ''v'' and there is a vertex ''w'' such that ''u'' ≤ ''w'' and ''v'' ≤ ''w''.
Bound graphs are sometimes referred to as ''upper bound graphs'', but the analogously defined '''lower bound graphs''' comprise exactly the same class—any lower bound for ≤ is easily seen to be an upper bound for the [[duality (order theory)|dual]] partial order ≥.
